  <!-- ═══ SECTION 1: THE EMOTIONAL HOOK ═══ -->
  <p>I was seven years old the first time I watched someone I loved struggle to breathe.</p>

  <p>My grandma Shugy (her real name was Charlotte, but to me she was just Shugy) had a tube running into her nose and a cough that sounded like it came from somewhere deep and broken.</p>

  <p>I didn't know what emphysema was. I just knew she always smelled like smoke, always had butterscotch candies in her purse, and always seemed tired.</p>

  <p><strong>And then one morning, she was gone.</strong></p>

  <p>I didn't get to say goodbye. I was too young to understand what had happened. All I knew was that the woman who held me on her lap every Sunday was never coming back.</p>

  <p>I thought it was a one-time tragedy. Something that just happened to our family.</p>

  <p><strong>I was wrong.</strong></p>

  <div class="prl-divider"></div>

  <!-- ── IMAGE 2: Grandma Shugy ── -->
  <div class="prl-img-block">
    <img
      src="https://assets.replocdn.com/projects/6bf67db6-09d6-4705-bab2-a1af9067f5a3/5df22432-8c44-4d5a-8cff-42a9c86f651e"
      alt="Family photo, Grandma Shugy"
      loading="lazy"
    />
  </div>

  <p><strong>Then I lost my Aunt Theresa.</strong></p>

  <p>Same cause. Decades of cigarettes. A chronic cough that turned into chronic bronchitis, and lungs that slowly gave up.</p>

  <p>I was older this time. Old enough to notice the pattern. Old enough to be angry.</p>

  <!-- ── IMAGE 3: Aunt Theresa ── -->
  <div class="prl-img-block">
    <img
      src="https://assets.replocdn.com/projects/6bf67db6-09d6-4705-bab2-a1af9067f5a3/e223925d-5c03-4174-9943-035bec856eea"
      alt="Family photo, Aunt Theresa"
      loading="lazy"
    />
  </div>

  <p><strong>Then I lost my Aunt Deb.</strong></p>

  <p>Emphysema. Then a stroke. The same slow, suffocating decline I'd already watched twice.</p>

  <!-- ── IMAGE 4: Aunt Deb ── -->
  <div class="prl-img-block">
    <img
      src="https://assets.replocdn.com/projects/6bf67db6-09d6-4705-bab2-a1af9067f5a3/62102243-44ad-48fe-a269-7bb9af4841b6"
      alt="Family photo, Aunt Deb"
      loading="lazy"
    />
  </div>

  <p>Three women. Three funerals. Three times standing in a room full of people who didn't know what to say.</p>

  <p><strong>Same cause every single time.</strong></p>

