  <p>So I did what I was trained to do. I went back to the research.</p>

  <p>Not the headlines. Not the wellness blogs. The actual peer-reviewed literature on respiratory support.</p>

  <p>And I found something that kept showing up, a plant that had been used for lung conditions since ancient Greece, but had been largely overlooked by modern medicine.</p>

  <p><strong>Mullein leaf.</strong></p>

  <p>Specifically, the saponins in mullein. They do two critical things most remedies don't:</p>

  <p><strong>First</strong>, they decrease mucus viscosity, making the thick, sticky buildup in your airways thinner and easier to move.</p>

  <p><strong>Second</strong>, they increase cilia activity, waking up those tiny cleaning hairs that have been flattened by years of smoke, so your lungs can actually start expelling what's been trapped.</p>

  <p>Most lung supplements throw 12 ingredients at the wall and hope something sticks. But the research kept pointing me back to this one plant, and to one companion ingredient that made it work even harder:</p>

  <p><strong>Chlorophyll.</strong></p>

  <p>Not the trendy wellness drink version. The real thing, shown to support oxygenation at the cellular level and deliver antioxidant properties that help combat the oxidative damage smoking leaves behind.</p>

  <p>Two ingredients. Working on two different pathways. One clears the wreckage. The other helps rebuild.</p>

  <p><strong>This wasn't complicated. It was overlooked.</strong></p>

